In mammalian species, inflammation is a natural defensive cellular mechanism against harmful factors such as physical or noxious chemical stimuli and pathogens. During the inflammation process, macrophage cells have been considered as the key component of the host immune system (
Medzhitov, 2010
; Moghaddam et al., 2018). However, the uncontrolled inflammatory response of macrophages to pathogenic substances such as bacterial lipopolysaccharides (LPS) can lead to multiple inflammatory diseases, such as cardiovascular disease (
Okamoto et al., 2007
; 
Soysal et al., 2020
), arthritis (
Skeoch et al., 2015
), and asthma (
Saradna et al., 2018
; 
Fricker et al., 2017
), 
via
expression of pro-inflammatory enzymes. For example, the inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS) catalyzes the production of excessive NO, and pro-inflammatory cytokines, such as tumor necrosis factor (TNF- 
α
), interleukin 6 (IL-6) and interleukin 1β (IL-1β) which cause cell damage (
Liu et al., 2017
). These inflammatory factors are induced by the nuclear factor κB (NF-κB), which is an important dimeric transcription factor involved in the inflammatory responses. The NF-κB complexes, consisting of NF-κB and the inhibitor of NF-κB (IκB), may be degraded via phosphorylation triggered by interaction with IκB kinase (IκK), thus inducing NF-κB translocation to the nucleus (
Liu et al., 2017
; Karin et al., 2000). Therefore, the NF-κB signaling cascade may be an important target for preventing inflammatory diseases.

